# Cursor Rules: Security Standards

rules:
  - id: security.authentication.api_keys
    description: |
      API key management must follow strict security practices.
      - API keys must be stored in environment variables or secure secrets management
      - Never hardcode API keys in source code or configuration files
      - Never log API keys or include them in error messages
      - Use strong, randomly generated API keys (minimum 32 characters)
      - Rotate API keys regularly and support key rotation without downtime
      - Validate API keys using constant-time comparison to prevent timing attacks
      - Support API key revocation and expiration
    severity: error

  - id: security.authentication.validation
    description: |
      Authentication validation must be secure and consistent.
      - Validate API keys on all protected endpoints
      - Use dependency injection for authentication to ensure consistency
      - Return generic error messages for authentication failures (do not reveal if key exists)
      - Implement rate limiting on authentication endpoints
      - Log authentication failures for security monitoring
      - Support optional authentication where appropriate (validate if provided)
    severity: error

  - id: security.data.sensitive_information
    description: |
      Sensitive information must be handled securely.
      - Never log sensitive data (API keys, passwords, tokens, PII)
      - Sanitize sensitive data in error messages and stack traces
      - Use secure storage for sensitive configuration
      - Encrypt sensitive data at rest when required
      - Use secure transmission (HTTPS/TLS) for sensitive data in transit
      - Implement data retention policies for sensitive information
    severity: error

  - id: security.data.input_sanitization
    description: |
      All user inputs must be validated and sanitized.
      - Validate all inputs using Pydantic models or similar validation
      - Sanitize inputs to prevent injection attacks (SQL, command, template injection)
      - Validate input types, ranges, and formats
      - Reject malformed or suspicious inputs
      - Use parameterized queries/operations to prevent injection
      - Limit input size to prevent resource exhaustion attacks
    severity: error

  - id: security.data.output_encoding
    description: |
      Output must be properly encoded to prevent injection attacks.
      - Encode all user-generated content in responses
      - Use appropriate encoding for different contexts (HTML, JSON, URLs)
      - Validate and sanitize data before including in error messages
      - Use framework-provided encoding mechanisms (FastAPI, Pydantic)
    severity: warning

  - id: security.dependencies.vulnerability_management
    description: |
      Dependencies must be kept secure and up-to-date.
      - Regularly audit dependencies for known vulnerabilities
      - Use dependency scanning tools (e.g., safety, pip-audit)
      - Update dependencies promptly when security patches are available
      - Pin dependency versions in requirements files
      - Document security-related dependency updates
      - Review and approve all new dependencies before adding
    severity: error

  - id: security.dependencies.trust
    description: |
      Only trusted dependencies should be used.
      - Use well-maintained, reputable packages from PyPI
      - Review dependency licenses for compliance
      - Avoid dependencies with known security issues
      - Prefer dependencies with active maintenance and security practices
      - Document rationale for security-sensitive dependencies
    severity: warning

  - id: security.configuration.secrets_management
    description: |
      Secrets must be managed securely.
      - Store secrets in environment variables or secure secrets management systems
      - Never commit secrets to version control
      - Use `.env` files for local development (excluded from git)
      - Rotate secrets regularly
      - Use different secrets for different environments
      - Document secret requirements in deployment guides
    severity: error

  - id: security.configuration.environment
    description: |
      Configuration must be secure across environments.
      - Use environment-specific configuration
      - Validate configuration on startup
      - Use secure defaults (e.g., require authentication in production)
      - Document security-relevant configuration options
      - Audit configuration changes
    severity: warning

  - id: security.api.endpoint_protection
    description: |
      API endpoints must be appropriately protected.
      - Protect sensitive endpoints with authentication
      - Implement rate limiting on public endpoints
      - Use HTTPS in production environments
      - Validate and sanitize all inputs
      - Implement request size limits
      - Use CORS appropriately (restrictive in production)
    severity: error

  - id: security.api.error_messages
    description: |
      API error messages must not leak sensitive information.
      - Use generic error messages for authentication failures
      - Do not reveal system internals in error messages
      - Log detailed errors internally, return sanitized errors to users
      - Use error codes for programmatic error handling
      - Avoid exposing stack traces or internal paths in production
    severity: error

  - id: security.module.isolation
    description: |
      Module execution must be isolated and secure.
      - Validate all module inputs before execution
      - Limit resource usage (CPU, memory, time) for module operations
      - Isolate module execution when possible (sandboxing for untrusted modules)
      - Validate module code before loading (when loading dynamic modules)
      - Implement module permission system for sensitive operations
    severity: warning

  - id: security.module.code_execution
    description: |
      Code execution must be secure and controlled.
      - Use sandboxed environments for code execution
      - Validate and sanitize code before execution
      - Limit code execution resources (time, memory, network access)
      - Audit code execution for security monitoring
      - Implement code execution policies and restrictions
    severity: error

  - id: security.logging.sensitive_data
    description: |
      Logging must not expose sensitive information.
      - Never log API keys, passwords, tokens, or PII
      - Sanitize sensitive data in log messages
      - Use structured logging with appropriate log levels
      - Implement log access controls
      - Rotate and secure log files
      - Audit log access
    severity: error

  - id: security.logging.security_events
    description: |
      Security-relevant events must be logged.
      - Log authentication failures and successes
      - Log authorization failures
      - Log suspicious activities (repeated failures, unusual patterns)
      - Log security configuration changes
      - Use appropriate log levels for security events
      - Monitor security logs for anomalies
    severity: warning

  - id: security.audit.requirements
    description: |
      Security audits must be conducted regularly.
      - Perform security code reviews for security-sensitive changes
      - Conduct dependency vulnerability scans regularly
      - Review authentication and authorization logic
      - Audit configuration and secrets management
      - Document security audit findings and remediation
    severity: warning

  - id: security.incident.response
    description: |
      Security incidents must be handled according to established procedures.
      - Document security incident response procedures
      - Report security vulnerabilities responsibly
      - Implement security monitoring and alerting
      - Maintain incident logs and post-mortems
      - Update security practices based on incident learnings
    severity: warning

examples:
  - description: "Secure API key validation"
    language: python
    code: |
      import os
      import hmac
      import hashlib
      from fastapi import HTTPException, Header
      from typing import Optional
      
      
      def verify_api_key_secure(
          authorization: Optional[str] = Header(None),
          expected_key: Optional[str] = None
      ) -> bool:
          """
          Verify API key using constant-time comparison to prevent timing attacks
          
          Args:
              authorization: Authorization header value
              expected_key: Expected API key (from environment)
          
          Returns:
              True if API key is valid
          
          Raises:
              HTTPException: If authentication fails
          """
          if not expected_key:
              expected_key = os.getenv("MAVAIA_API_KEY")
          
          if not expected_key:
              # No key configured, allow if not required
              return True
          
          if not authorization or not authorization.startswith("Bearer "):
              raise HTTPException(
                  status_code=401,
                  detail="Invalid authorization header"
              )
          
          provided_key = authorization.replace("Bearer ", "").strip()
          
          # Use constant-time comparison to prevent timing attacks
          if not hmac.compare_digest(provided_key, expected_key):
              raise HTTPException(
                  status_code=401,
                  detail="Invalid API key"
              )
          
          return True

  - description: "Input validation and sanitization"
    language: python
    code: |
      from pydantic import BaseModel, validator, Field
      from typing import Optional
      import re
      
      
      class SafeInputRequest(BaseModel):
          """Request model with input validation and sanitization"""
          
          text: str = Field(..., min_length=1, max_length=10000)
          module_name: str = Field(..., pattern=r"^[a-z0-9_]+$")
          operation: Optional[str] = Field(None, pattern=r"^[a-z0-9_]+$")
          
          @validator("text")
          def sanitize_text(cls, v):
              """Sanitize text input"""
              # Remove potentially dangerous characters
              v = re.sub(r'[<>"\']', '', v)
              # Limit length
              if len(v) > 10000:
                  raise ValueError("Text too long")
              return v.strip()
          
          @validator("module_name", "operation")
          def validate_identifier(cls, v):
              """Validate identifier format"""
              if v and not re.match(r'^[a-z0-9_]+$', v):
                  raise ValueError("Invalid identifier format")
              return v

  - description: "Secure logging without sensitive data"
    language: python
    code: |
      import logging
      from typing import Any, Dict
      
      logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)
      
      
      def sanitize_for_logging(data: Dict[str, Any]) -> Dict[str, Any]:
          """Remove sensitive data from logging context"""
          sensitive_keys = {"api_key", "password", "token", "secret", "authorization"}
          sanitized = {}
          for key, value in data.items():
              if any(sensitive in key.lower() for sensitive in sensitive_keys):
                  sanitized[key] = "***REDACTED***"
              else:
                  sanitized[key] = value
          return sanitized
      
      
      def log_operation(operation: str, context: Dict[str, Any]):
          """Log operation with sanitized context"""
          sanitized_context = sanitize_for_logging(context)
          logger.info(
              f"Operation: {operation}",
              extra={"operation": operation, "context": sanitized_context}
          )

